<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-508-052  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 508 052.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  June 4 1990 v7 n23 p4(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Aggregators facing future clouded by new uncertainty. (long-haultelecommunications carriers perceive call aggregators as threat)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brown, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The call aggregation industry is comprised of companies thatcombine network traffic of multiple users in order to qualify fordiscounts on telecommunications services from ATandamp;T, MCI Corp andUS Sprint Communications Co. ATandamp;T initially supported theactivities of aggregators when it seemed they would expand itsmarket share, but since 1989 it has been apparent that aggregatorsare actually competing with the long-haul carriers for the samebusiness, leading to speculation that ATandamp;T will try to curtailaggregator activity.andP;  ATandamp;T has already lowered its ceiling figuresto make it easier for companies to get bulk rates without goingthrough an aggregator.andP;  The threat from the big carriers has ledto speedy consolidation among aggregators and a push to offeradditional services such as consulting and re-billing.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (market share).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     CompetitionTelecommunicationsTelephone CompaniesMarketing StrategyDiscountCost of Communications.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>